      <abstract>
        <para>
          This guide introduces &slcs;&mdash;its deployment, subscription,
          system management, available collections of container workloads, as
          well as details about applications delivered as RPM packages.
        </para>
        <variablelist>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>WHAT?</term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                &slcs; is a Linux distribution for running containerized
                workloads. It consists of &slm; and &slcc; and is easy to deploy
                and maintain.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>WHY?</term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                You want to learn
              </para>
              <itemizedlist>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    what &slcs; is in detail.
                  </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    how to deploy &slcs;.
                  </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    how to administer common &slcs; system management tasks.
                  </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    how to deploy and run containerized workloads on &slcs;.
                  </para>
                </listitem>
                <listitem>
                  <para>
                    how to manage applications deployed as RPM packages.
                  </para>
                </listitem>
              </itemizedlist>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>EFFORT</term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                It takes less than 5 minutes to understand what &slcs; is and
                what benefits it offers.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
          <varlistentry>
            <term>REQUIREMENTS</term>
            <listitem>
              <para>
                To understand the concepts and perform tasks described in this
                guide, you need to have good knowledge and practice with the
                &suse; Linux operating system.
              </para>
            </listitem>
          </varlistentry>
        </variablelist>
